column1: Growth development problem, eg slow growth (before birth(intrauterine) or after birth, growth spurt (adolescent)), rapid growth and overgrowth (macrosomia), early growth, growth failure and delayed growth. Reduced puberty growth, lack of growth spurt

Underdevelopment (Hypoplasia) : a flat or sunken appearance of the middle of the face (midface hypoplasia); muscle hypoplasia; underdevelopment of the region at the back of the eye responsible for sharp central vision (foveal hypoplasia); thin enamel on the teeth (enamel hypoplasia); hypoplasia of cerebellum and the pons; underdevelopment of the nerves that carry information from the eyes to the brain (optic nerve hypoplasia); (hypoplasia) of the tips of the fingers or toes, or hypoplasia or absence of the nails; corpus callosum hypoplasia; underdevelopment of the lungs (pulmonary hypoplasia); underdevelopment of one side of the upper or lower jaw (maxillary or mandibular hypoplasia);  thin or missing patches of skin on the scalp (dermal hypoplasia or aplasia); underdeveloped thumbs (thumb hypoplasia); very thin skin (dermal hypoplasia); focal dermal hypoplasia; underdevelopment of pituitary gland (pituitary hypoplasia);  hypoplasia of Leydig cells in the testes; cerebellar hypoplasia;   malar hypoplasia; mandibular hypoplasia, also called micrognathia; hypoplasia of the labia majora; (hypoplasia) of a peg-like bone in the neck called the odontoid process; heart, lung, brain underdevelopment; thyroid; (hypoplasia) of one or both kidneys; genital hypoplasia; bones of the skull; scrotum; underdevelopment of the wing-shaped structures of pelvis (hypoplastic iliac wings); ear canal
Reduced production of hormones directs sexual development (hypogonadotropic hypogonadism);

deformities of joint that limiting movement (contractures) of hips, knees, ankles, or elbows; distal arthrogryposis; (camptodactyly), bent fingers and toes hand deformity in which all of the fingers are angled outward toward the fifth finger (ulnar deviation, also called "windmill vane hand");  inward- and downward-turning feet (clubfoot); contractures in the legs and hips; turning in (valgus deformity) of the feet; contractures affecting elbows and wrists
Developmental delays: delayed development of mental and motor skills such as crawling, sitting, standing, holding up the head and rolling over,reaching for a toy and walking (psychomotor)
Developmental delays: delayed development of speech
heart defect: (ASD) artricular septal defects or ventricular septal defects (VSD)
Shaking; Rhythmic shaking; tremor; trembling 震顫
bone abnormalities in their hands and arms
intention tremor; involuntary rhythmic shaking; tremor occurs during movement
postural tremor; shaking when holding a position
problems with coordinating muscle movement and balance (ataxia)
opening of the urethra on the underside of the penis (hypospadias)
Abnormalities of the genitalia and urinary tract(genitourinary abnormalities) (genitourinary anomalies)
Inflammation of joints between spine and ribs
sacroiliac joints (joints between the pelvic bones (the ilia) and the base of the spine (the sacrum) ) inflammation (sacroiliitis)
Arthritis: Inflammation of the lining of joints (synovium)
Inflammation of the joints of the hands, feet, wrist and ankle (synovitis)
Charcot joints: bones and tissue surrounding joints are destroyed
degeneration of (avascular necrosis) of the hip and shoulder joints
enlarged wrist and ankled knee and ankle joints
webbing of the skin (pterygium) at the joints
abnormal wrist and elbow joint development

Poor muscle tone; Uncontrolled muscle tensing/cramping/contraction (dystonia): cervical dystonia, focal dystonia of hand; dystonia affecting arms and legs; Musician's dystonia is a form of task-specific focal dystonia; embouchure dystonia
abnormal development of bone marrow cells called megakaryocytes
aplasia cutis congenita: abnormal skin development
teeth to be unusually small, discolored, pitted or grooved,  and prone to rapid wear and breakage
Abnormal development of ectodermal tissues including the skin, hair, teeth, and sweat

Abnormal development of the ears and lower jaw (mandible);abnormality called a "question-mark ear," in which the ears have a distinctive question-mark shape caused by a split that separates the upper part of the ear from the earlobe
small skin tags in front of or behind the ears
loss of underarm and pubic hair
narrowing of the eye opening (blepharophimosis), droopy eyelids (ptosis), and an upward fold of the skin of the lower eyelid near the inner corner of the eye (epicanthus inversus)
unusually small eyeballs (microphthalmia),(anophthalmia), a gap or split in structures that make up the eyes (coloboma) or blockage of the tear ducts (nasolacrimal duct stenosis).
abnormal development of the second branchial arch forming masses in the neck called branchial cleft cysts.
increased pressure within the skull (intracranial pressure)
development of small yellow deposits of fat under the skin called eruptive xanthomas
sparse hair, small or missing teeth, short fingernails and toenails, and loose skin.
developmental abnormalities involving the skull (cranium) and face
problems with regulating blood sugar levels
development of inward- and upward-turning feet (clubfeet)
development of a noncancerous tumor in the pituitary gland (pituitary adenoma)
abnormal eye development, including missing eyebrows or eyelashes or a patch of hair extending from the side hairline to the eyebrow.
abnormal development of the ovaries (polycystic ovaries)
malformation of the hands and feet called ectrodactyly.
multiple abnormalities in the blood vessels
development of swellings called spheroid bodies in the axons, the fibers that extend from nerve cells (neurons)
abnormal development of the ovaries (ovarian dysgenesis)
abnormal development of arms,  resulting in characteristic arm malformations
painful bumps or blisters on the face, neck, back, and arms.
disability that ranges from mild to severe
problems with the development of the roof of the mouth (palate), and
abnormally smooth brain with fewer folds and grooves (lissencephaly)
premature closure of certain bones of the skull (craniosynostosis)
abnormal development of the Müllerian ducts, which are structures in the embryo that develop into the uterus, fallopian tubes, cervix, and the upper part of the vagina.
underdeveloped or absent uterus and may also have abnormalities of other reproductive organs
abnormal development of normal blood cells
narrowing (stenosis) of the heart valves or blood vessels
abnormal development of retina: immature retinal cells accumulating at the back of the eye
problems with development of the oral cavity
problems with the development of blood-forming cells
cloudy cornea (opaque) which causes blurred vision
underdevelopment of the tissue connecting the left and right halves of the brain (corpus callosum),
underdevelopment or absence of the bones in the forearms and the thumbs, which are known as radial ray malformations

patchy white matter abnormalities (lesions) in the brain
development of bones in the spine and ribs ie mishapen and abnormally joint the bones of the spine (vertebrae)
lack of development of the gonads
development of female secondary sex characteristics
underdevelopment of the facial bones that  may restrict an affected infant's airway causing potentially life-threatening respiratory problems.
